==Grammar==
{{Main|Ugaritic grammar}}
Ugaritic is an [[inflection|inflected language]], and its grammatical features are highly similar to those found in [[Classical Arabic]] and [[Akkadian (language)|Akkadian]]. It possesses two [[grammatical gender|genders]] (masculine and feminine), three [[grammatical case]]s for [[noun]]s and [[adjective]]s ([[nominative case|nominative]], [[accusative case|accusative]], and [[genitive case|genitive]]), three [[grammatical number|numbers]] (singular, dual, and plural), and [[grammatical aspect|verb aspects]] similar to those found in other [[Northwest Semitic languages|Northwest Semitic]] languages. The [[word order]] for Ugaritic is [[verb–subject–object]] (VSO) and [[subject–object–verb]] (SOV),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wilson|first1=Gerald H.|title=Ugaritic Word Order and Sentence Structure in KRT|journal=Journal of Semitic Studies|date=1982|volume=27|issue=1|pages=17–32|doi=10.1093/jss/27.1.17}}</ref> [[possession (linguistics)|possessed–possessor]] (NG), and [[noun]]–[[adjective]] (NA). Ugaritic is considered a conservative Semitic language, since it retains most of the [[Proto-Semitic language#Phonology|phonemes]], the case system, and the word order of the ancestral [[Proto-Semitic language]].

